See how that compares to the text in the PDF on Page 9. What has pdftools added and where?

From Jessica and Caseyâs text mining workshop: âpdf_text() returns a vector of strings, one for each page of the pdf. So we can mess with it in tidyverse style, letâs turn it into a dataframe, and keep track of the pages. Then we can use stringr::str_split() to break the pages up into individual lines. Each line of the pdf is concluded with a backslash-n, so split on this. We will also add a line number in addition to the page number.â

Some wrangling:

  • Split up pages into separate lines (separated by \n) using stringr::str_split()
  • Unnest into regular columns using tidyr::unnest()
  • Remove leading/trailing white space with stringr::str_trim()
#Note: vi laver det til en data.frame sÃ¥ det bliver til en kolonne. sÃ¥ bruer vi 'mutat' til at lave en ny kolonne (hvor hver linje bliver en rÃ¦kke i denne kolonne), og vi bruger /n til at indikere hvor linjerne skal dele. 
got_df <- data.frame(got_text) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_split(got_text, pattern = '\n')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full))

Get the tokens (individual words) in tidy format

Use tidytext::unnest_tokens() (which pulls from the tokenizer) package, to split columns into tokens. We are interested in words, so thatâs the token weâll use:

#vi tgaer dataframe og den nye kolonne vi har lavet 'text_full' og laver en ny kolonne kaldet 'word'. Nu er linjerne eksploderet til individuelle ord, i 'word' kolonnen.

got_tokens <- got_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full)

Sentiment analysis

First, check out the âsentimentsâ lexicon. From Julia Silge and David Robinson (https://www.tidytextmining.com/sentiment.html):

âThe three general-purpose lexicons are

  • AFINN from Finn Ãrup Nielsen,
  • bing from Bing Liu and collaborators, and
  • nrc from Saif Mohammad and Peter Turney

All three of these lexicons are based on unigrams, i.e., single words. These lexicons contain many English words and the words are assigned scores for positive/negative sentiment, and also possibly emotions like joy, anger, sadness, and so forth. The AFINN lexicon assigns words with a score that runs between -5 and 5, with negative scores indicating negative sentiment and positive scores indicating positive sentiment. The bing lexicon categorizes words in a binary fashion into positive and negative categories. The nrc lexicon categorizes words in a binary fashion (âyesâ/ânoâ) into categories of positive, negative, anger, anticipation, disgust, fear, joy, sadness, surprise, and trust. All of this information is tabulated in the sentiments dataset, and tidytext provides a function get_sentiments() to get specific sentiment lexicons without the columns that are not used in that lexicon.â

Letâs explore the sentiment lexicons. âbingâ is included, other lexicons (âafinnâ, ânrcâ, âloughranâ) youâll be prompted to download.

WARNING: These collections include very offensive words. I urge you to not look at them in class.

# OK so what's the deal with confidence? And is it really "positive" in the emotion sense?

Look back at the IPCC report, and search for âconfidence.â Is it typically associated with emotion, or something else?

We learn something important from this example: Just using a sentiment lexicon to match words will not differentiate between different uses of the wordâ¦(ML can start figuring it out with context, but we wonât do that here).

Or we can summarize sentiment for the report:

got_summary <- got_afinn %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_score = mean(value),
    median_score = median(value)
  )

The mean and median indicate slightly positive overall sentiments based on the AFINN lexicon.

NRC lexicon for sentiment analysis

We can use the NRC lexicon to start âbinningâ text by the feelings theyâre typically associated with. As above, weâll use inner_join() to combine the IPCC non-stopword text with the nrc lexicon:

got_nrc <- got_stop %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc"))

Wait, wonât that exclude some of the words in our text? YES! We should check which are excluded using anti_join():

got_exclude <- got_nrc %>% 
  full_join(get_sentiments("nrc"))

view(got_exclude)

Lesson: always check which words are EXCLUDED in sentiment analysis using a pre-built lexicon!

  count(sentiment, sort = TRUE)

Or count by sentiment and word, then facet:

got_nrc_n5 <- got_nrc %>% 
  count(word,sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(sentiment) %>% 
  top_n(5) %>% 
  ungroup()

got_nrc_gg <- ggplot(data = got_nrc_n5, aes(x = reorder(word,n), y = n, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, ncol = 2, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Word", y = "count")

# Show it
got_nrc_gg

# Save it
ggsave(plot = got_nrc_gg, 
       here("figures","frank_nrc_sentiment.png"), 
       height = 8, 
       width = 5)

Big picture takeaway

There are serious limitations of sentiment analysis using existing lexicons, and you should think really hard about your findings and if a lexicon makes sense for your study. Otherwise, word counts and exploration alone can be useful!
